<p>I have the following HTML:</p>  <pre><code>&lt;div id="foo"&gt;     &lt;span&gt;         &lt;a href="#" class="no-want"&gt;X&lt;/a&gt;         &amp;nbsp;         1     &lt;/span&gt;     &lt;span&gt;         &lt;a href="#" class="no-want"&gt;X&lt;/a&gt;         &amp;nbsp;         2     &lt;/span&gt;     &lt;span&gt;         &lt;a href="#" class="no-want"&gt;X&lt;/a&gt;         &amp;nbsp;         Hello     &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/div&gt;  </code></pre>  <p>I want to use jQuery to get only the following <code>1</code>, <code>2</code> and <code>hello</code> in JS (that means no <code>&lt;a&gt;</code> tags or <code>&amp;nbsp;</code>). Please note that <em>I do not want to affect the DOM itself</em>.  I just want to retrieve the text in an object such as an array.</p>  <p>This is what I have so far:</p>  <pre><code>$('#foo span'); </code></pre>  <p>However I can't seem to remove the "a" tag.</p>  <p>The following does not seem to work either:</p>  <pre><code>$('#foo span').remove('a'); </code></pre>  <p>I'm also aware that <code>.remove()</code> affects the DOM it self, and does not just retrieve the text.</p>